Week 3 - Kaggle Mini Project: Histopathologic Cancer Detection¶

Note: This project is part of a peer-reviewed assignment in week 3 of the course "Introduction to Deep Learning" from the CU Boulder, which counts towards the Master of Science in Data Science (MSDS) degree.

In this work, the Histopathologic Cancer Detection kaggle challenge is used, with the goal being able to "identify metastatic tissue in histopathologic scans of lymph node sections". The challenge is described as follows:

In this competition, you must create an algorithm to identify metastatic cancer in small image patches taken from larger digital pathology scans. The data for this competition is a slightly modified version of the PatchCamelyon (PCam) benchmark dataset (the original PCam dataset contains duplicate images due to its probabilistic sampling, however, the version presented on Kaggle does not contain duplicates).

PCam is highly interesting for both its size, simplicity to get started on, and approachability. [...]

1) Brief Description of the Problem and Data¶

AI has been widely used for medical image processing in recent years. This is due to the fact that AI models are able to match, or even surpass, expert-like accuracies in that field of application. This mini project is used as an introduction to medical image processing, using images from pathologic scans of lymph node sections. The goal is to classify the images with corresponding labels 0 (no cancer) and 1 (cancerous) using convolutional neural networks (CNN).

The training dataset consists of roughly 220.000 RGB images with dimension (96, 96, 3) and binary labels. "A positive label indicates that the center 32x32px region of a patch contains at least one pixel of tumor tissue."

The test dataset of size ~57.000 is unlabeled and used to determine the score of the challenge. The scoring metric is the area under ROC.

A more detailed analysis - including example images - of the dataset can be found in the next section.

2) Exploratory Data Anaylsis (EDA), Visualizations, Cleaning and Preprocessing.¶

From the EDA, we see that the training dataset is approximately balanced with slightly more non-cancerous labels. Note that this does not reflect the real distribution of such an analysis, but is rather an effect of sampling and collecting the data. There are no missing labels.

Further obvious cleaning steps are not necessary, besides dropping erroneous images that came up during training.

However, the description states that the cancerous cell is located in a 32x32 box in the center of the image, so cropping the original images to the section of interest reduces the computation effort for training and tuning. Further preprocessing steps include splitting the training set into a train and validation set for hyperparameter tuning.

# Preprocessing: Create image generator, and make train-valid-split (cropping is applied within the model)

BATCH_SIZE = 128

def crop_fn(img):
    return tf.image.central_crop(img, CROP_RATE)

gen = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1./255.,
    validation_split=0.2,
    #preprocessing_function=crop_fn # crop images from center
)

gen_train = gen.flow_from_dataframe(
    dataframe=df_train,
    directory=path_train,
    x_col="id",
    y_col="label",
    subset="training",
    target_size=(96,96),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    seed=42,
    class_mode="binary")

gen_valid = gen.flow_from_dataframe(
    dataframe=df_train,
    directory=path_train,
    x_col="id",
    y_col="label",
    subset="validation",
    target_size=(96,96),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    seed=42,
    class_mode="binary")

3) Model Architecture¶

For this demo project, I am using a straight-forward CNN approach with similar state-of-the-art techniques to established CNN models such as AlexNet, i.e. increasing the number of kernels in each layer and adding dropout and pooling layers for regularization. The most important hyperparameters can be modified in order to make tuning them more efficient. To simplify things, I am fixing the number of convolutional layers to three, and the number of dense layers to two as well as the kernel size to (3,3), pooling size to (2,2) activation function to ReLU and Adam as optimizer.

A pretty shallow model with only about 10.300 parameters gets an already quite decent validation AUC of 0.8872.

# Define model

def get_model(n_filt_1=8, n_filt_2=8, n_filt_3=16, n_dense=32, dropout_rate=0.2, lr_adam=0.0001):
    # returns compiled model with hyperparameters according to inputs

    mod = tf.keras.Sequential()
    
    # Cropping
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.Lambda(lambda img: tf.image.central_crop(img, CROP_RATE)))
    
    # Convolutional Layer 1
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=n_filt_1, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(dropout_rate))
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
    
    # Convolutional Layer 2
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=n_filt_2, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.AveragePooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(dropout_rate))
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
    
    # Convolutional Layer 3
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=n_filt_3, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.AveragePooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(dropout_rate))
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())    
    
    # Dense Layer
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.Flatten())
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(n_dense, activation='relu'))
    
    # Output Layer
    mod.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    
    mod.build(input_shape=(BATCH_SIZE, 96, 96, 3)) 
    
    opt = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr_adam)
    mod.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy', tf.keras.metrics.AUC()], optimizer=opt)

    print(mod.summary())
    
    return mod

baseline_model = get_model()

def plot_learning_curve(hist):
    history = hist.history
    plt.plot(history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history['val_loss'])
    plt.title('Learning Curve')
    plt.ylabel('loss')
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.legend(['training', 'validation'], loc='upper left')
    plt.show();
    
plot_learning_curve(baseline_hist)

4) Tuning, Results and Analysis¶

Even with center-cropping and a small model, training a single epoch on my device took quite a long time. For this reason, I decided to train only one additional model with a larger number of parameters to see how much more performance can be gained by increasing the total number of trainable parameters.

The deeper model gets AUC scores of around 0.90, which suggests that even deeper models (and more epochs) would increase the accuracy further.

5) Prediction and Conclusion¶

This mini project was quite enjoyable, especially because it was fun to work with real-world medical images. It could be seen that decent scores can be achieved using CNNs. However, improving the model further is quite time consuming, because of the large training times. Apart from tuning the model architecture, several image preprocessing techniques could be applied to improve the dataset. This can be seen by looking at other solutions from this public playground competition. Without using leaked labels, accuracies >0.98 are achievable.
